<methodology slug="storytelling">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Structure business narratives to lead with conclusions first, supported by evidence. Three frameworks: Pyramid Principle, SCQA, and Pixar for different narrative contexts.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>storytelling</tag>
      <tag>narrative</tag>
      <tag>business-writing</tag>
      <tag>presentations</tag>
      <tag>executive-communication</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Business Storytelling</title>
    <summary>People remember stories 22x better than facts alone. Business storytelling uses three complementary frameworks—Pyramid Principle for logic-driven decisions, SCQA for narrative tension, and Pixar for case studies—to lead with conclusions and support with evidence. Every claim must pass the "so what" test: a fact without an implication is incomplete.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Audiences disengage when they must read through background to reach the conclusion. Leading with the answer lets busy readers stop when satisfied; the supporting structure provides depth for those who continue. Data storytelling fails when metrics are presented without implications—"99.9% uptime" means nothing until translated to "fewer than 9 hours of downtime per year."</p>
      <p>The core insight is that business narratives must be audience-first: readers decide within the first 30 seconds whether to engage, and if the recommendation is buried, it is often missed entirely. Pyramid Principle, SCQA, and Pixar all reverse the academic default (background first, conclusion last) and force the writer to lead with what matters.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Drafting executive summaries, board updates, or investor pitches that must lead with a recommendation</item>
        <item>Rewriting data-heavy reports that list facts without explaining implications</item>
        <item>Structuring product launch announcements or case studies for technical or non-technical audiences</item>
        <item>Preparing presentations where hook, problem, and call-to-action must be clearly separated</item>
        <item>Writing SCQA narrative for a strategy document, quarterly review, or proposal</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Purely operational documents (runbooks, incident postmortems, API docs) where narrative adds no value</item>
        <item>Legal or compliance documents where completeness and precision override persuasive flow</item>
        <item>Internal technical specs read by developers who need depth, not narrative arc</item>
        <item>High-context cultures (Japan, Korea) where "answer first" structure may read as presumptuous—adapt framing</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Pyramid Principle">
      <rule>
        <statement>Lead with the main point (answer/recommendation), then provide 2-4 supporting arguments, each backed by evidence. Arguments must be MECE: Mutually Exclusive (no overlap) and Collectively Exhaustive (nothing missing).</statement>
        <rationale>Busy readers get the answer immediately and can stop when satisfied. Bottom-up structure forces readers to process all evidence before reaching a conclusion they may reject.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Cloud migration proposal using Pyramid Principle">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[RECOMMENDATION: Migrate to cloud infrastructure by Q3.

ARGUMENT 1: 40% lower TCO
  Evidence: Internal TCO analysis vs current on-prem costs
  Evidence: Competitor benchmarks showing 35-45% savings

ARGUMENT 2: Eliminates current capacity ceiling
  Evidence: Current servers at 87% utilization peak
  Evidence: Projected 3x traffic growth in 18 months

ARGUMENT 3: Reduces deployment cycle from 2 weeks to 2 days
  Evidence: Deployment time comparison with cloud-native competitor
  Evidence: Developer survey: 68% cite deployment speed as top blocker]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Bottom-up structure—buries the answer">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Background: Our servers are aging...
Analysis: We compared three options...
Findings: Cloud showed cost savings...
Conclusion: We recommend migrating to cloud.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="SCQA Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Open with a Situation the audience accepts as true, introduce a Complication that creates tension, raise the Question that tension produces, then deliver the Answer. Never invent a complication where none exists.</statement>
        <rationale>SCQA creates narrative tension that makes the audience want the answer before it is given. Artificial complications undermine credibility.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="SCQA for a product quality proposal">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[S: Our team ships 10 features per quarter—strong velocity.
C: But 30% of features have critical bugs in the first week, eroding customer trust.
Q: How do we maintain velocity while improving quality?
A: Implement automated testing with an 80% coverage gate before any feature ships.]]></code>
      </example>
      <note>SCQA generates artificial narrative tension when the situation is genuinely stable; forcing "complication" where none exists undermines credibility. Use SCQA only when tension genuinely exists.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Pixar Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use the Pixar structure for case studies and change initiative stories: Once upon a time [situation] / Every day [routine] / One day [change] / Because of that [consequence 1] / Because of that [consequence 2] / Until finally [resolution].</statement>
        <rationale>The cause-effect chain of "Because of that" forces specificity about what the intervention actually changed, unlike generic "before/after" formats.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Pixar framework applied to a process automation story">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Once upon a time, our team spent 10 hours/week on manual reporting.
Every day, they copy-pasted data between 5 spreadsheets.
One day, we implemented automated dashboards.
Because of that, reporting time dropped to 1 hour/week.
Because of that, the team redirected 9 hours to analysis instead of data entry.
Until finally, they identified $500K in cost savings in Q4.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Hook techniques">
      <rule>
        <statement>The first 30 seconds must create a question in the audience's mind. Use a surprising statistic, a question, a bold claim, a micro-story, or a contradiction—never start by introducing yourself or the agenda.</statement>
        <rationale>Audiences decide within the first 30 seconds whether to engage. An agenda introduction signals "you can tune out for now."</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Surprising stat: "90% of startups fail in year 3. Here's what the 10% do differently."</item>
        <item>Question: "What if you could deploy without fear?"</item>
        <item>Bold claim: "Meetings are broken. I can prove it in 2 minutes."</item>
        <item>Micro-story: "Last Tuesday at 2am, our server crashed and no one knew for 4 hours."</item>
        <item>Contradiction: "The best code is no code."</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="The so-what test">
      <rule>
        <statement>For every data point, state the implication explicitly. A statistic without a "so what" is incomplete. The implication must be specific to the audience's context, not generic.</statement>
        <rationale>Audiences cannot reliably infer implications from raw numbers. Stating the implication removes ambiguity and prevents misreading.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[We have 99.9% uptime.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[99.9% uptime = fewer than 9 hours of downtime per year.
For our users: they will never see an error page during business hours.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Concrete vs abstract language">
      <rule>
        <statement>Replace abstract outcome language with specific measurements. Never use "improved efficiency", "better experience", or "enhanced performance" without a number attached.</statement>
        <rationale>Abstract language is unverifiable and unmemorable. Specific numbers are checkable and anchor the claim.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>"Improved efficiency" → "Cut processing time from 4 hours to 15 minutes"</item>
        <item>"Better customer experience" → "Reduced support tickets by 60%"</item>
        <item>"Enhanced security" → "Blocked 10,000 attacks last month"</item>
        <item>"Faster deploys" → "Deployment cycle: 2 weeks → 2 days"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Analogy rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Analogies must map to a domain the specific audience already understands. Test the analogy domain before using it; an analogy from an unfamiliar domain adds confusion instead of clarity.</statement>
        <rationale>An analogy works only if the audience can instantly map the source domain to the target. A mismatched analogy creates a second explanation problem.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Microservices analogy for a business audience familiar with restaurants">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Think of microservices like a restaurant kitchen.
Instead of one chef doing everything, you have specialists:
prep cook, grill cook, plating cook.
If orders spike at the grill station, you add one more grill cook—
not another full chef who has to learn the whole kitchen.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic workflow">
      <p>An agent producing a business narrative should receive the raw facts (data, situation, desired outcome) and apply the SCQA or Pyramid Principle framework in a single generation pass. For executive summaries, the agent leads with the recommendation, then generates supporting arguments that are MECE-checked. For case studies, the Pixar framework is applied: situation → routine → change → consequence chain → resolution. The agent should never pad a section with abstract language—every sentence must pass the "so what" test explicitly before output.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagent: faion-sdd-executor-agent can be directed to draft, then refine in a second pass where the agent checks each bullet for specificity and eliminates filler phrases.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best practices">
      <list>
        <item>Write the recommendation first, then gather supporting evidence—do not write background until the conclusion is locked</item>
        <item>Every data point must be paired with an implication statement ("so what"): "uptime is 99.9%" alone is incomplete; "this means fewer than 9 hours of downtime per year, invisible to users" is complete</item>
        <item>Use concrete numbers over percentages when the base is unknown to the reader: "3 of 10 users" is clearer than "30%"</item>
        <item>Analogies must map to concepts the specific audience already understands—test the analogy domain before using it</item>
        <item>The hook (first 30 seconds) must create a question in the reader's mind, not just introduce the speaker or the topic</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-agent gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents default to abstract, hedge-heavy language ("leverage synergies", "drive value")—instruct explicitly to use concrete numbers and specific outcomes only</item>
        <item>MECE validation requires domain knowledge the agent may not have; flag arguments for human MECE review before using in board-level documents</item>
        <item>Agents applying Pyramid Principle sometimes bury the recommendation in the third paragraph—always verify the first sentence states the conclusion</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint required before sending any externally-facing narrative document; agents cannot verify factual accuracy of metrics or competitive claims</item>
        <item>For presentations, agents produce slide text that is too dense for actual slides—add a post-processing step: "reduce each slide to one key point, max 20 words"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations and failure modes">
      <p>Pyramid Principle applied mechanically produces cold, robotic documents—it requires judgment about what the reader already knows. SCQA generates artificial narrative tension when the situation is genuinely stable; forcing "complication" where none exists undermines credibility. Data storytelling fails when the underlying metrics are contested—the story becomes a source of skepticism rather than persuasion. Business storytelling frameworks are culturally specific; high-context cultures (Japan, Korea) resist the "answer first" structure of Pyramid Principle.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/executive-summary.md" purpose="Executive summary structure: Recommendation → Context → Key Points → Next Steps"/>
      <template path="templates/case-study.md" purpose="Case study structure: Challenge → Solution → Results → Quote"/>
      <template path="templates/scqa.md" purpose="SCQA template with fill-in fields"/>
      <template path="templates/presentation-outline.md" purpose="Presentation outline: Hook → Problem → Solution → CTA"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-pyramid.txt" purpose="Prompt for applying Pyramid Principle to an executive summary"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-case-study.txt" purpose="Prompt for writing a Pixar-framework case study"/>
    </templates>
